DISCOVERED PACKAGE LEAKING IN UNLOAD.  TWO OF THE BOTTLES INSIDE THE CARTON HAD LOOSE LIDS CAUSING LIQUID TO LEAK OUT.  ALL OF THE SALVAGEABLE CONTENTS WERE REPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG AND PROCESSED IN DMP.

I RESPONDED USING THE DECISION TREE WEARING GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON AND BOOTS.  I IDENTIFIED THE MATERIAL AS CORROSIVE LIQUID.  I PLACED THE LEAKING JUGS IN A TUB.  I CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIALS USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AND SOLUSORB UNTILL THE PH TYPE WAS IN THE 6-9 RANGE.  I PLACED THE NEUTRALIZED MATERAIL INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DMP REMAINING CONTENTS WERE RTS.

NOVEMBER 5, 1995-DURING INSPECTION OF BAG CART 0036 LOCATED AT THE TWA MARSHALLING AREA ON HARDSTAND G, AT THE RAMP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE CARTON WAS IN DAMAGED CONDITION.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE OUTER CARTON WAS RIPPED AND THE INNER CONTENTS/PACKAGING MATERIAL WAS IN DISARRAY.  A BOTTLE CONTAINING LIQUID IN THE CARTON DID NOT APPEAR TO BE DAMAGED.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT HOLDING AREA IN TWA CARGO TERMINAL LOCATED AT HANGAR 12.  ATTEMPTS MADE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER ON THE EVENING OF 11/05/95 WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  NOVEMBER 6, 1995-DIAGNOSTIC IMAGING SERVICES WERE CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 EST.  THEY ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD SEND SOMEONE TO OUR FACILITY TO INSPECT THIS CARTON. AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 NOON EST, A REPRESENTATIVE CAME TO HANGAR 12 AND IDENTIFIED HIMSELF TO OUR SUPERVISOR.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO INSPECT THE DAMAGED CARTON AND ADVISED THAT HE DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT CARTON AND WOULD RETURN THE FOLLOWING MORNING, 11/07/95, TO REPACK THE SHIPMENT FOR MOVEMENT TO ST. LOUIS. NOVEMBER 7, 1995-AT 09:00 EST THE REPRESENTATIVE RETURNED WITH A TECHNICIAN FROM DIAGNOSTIC IMAGING.  THEY BEGUN INSPECTING THE CARTON WHICH WAS STILL IN THE HOLDING AREA FOR HAZMAT.  AT 09:30 EST THE TWA SHIFT MANAGER WAS ADVISED BY THE TECHNICIAN THAT THERE WAS AN EXPOSURE.  TWA SHIFT MANAGER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE FAA, PORT AUTHORITY AND SENIOR TWA MANAGEMENT OF THE SITUATION.  THE PORTION OF THE TWA TERMINAL WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING HELD, WAS CORDONED OFF FOR MORE THAT 6 HOURS BY THE PORT AUTHORITY. IT APPEARED THAT ALL FEDREAL AND LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE AT THE CARGO TERMINAL ON 11/07/95 TO INVESTIGATE THE EXPOSURE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKAGED BY DIAGNOSTIC IMAGING AND TESTED FOR EXPOSURE, WHICH WAS NIL. THE REPACKAGED SHIPMENT WAS THEN READY FOR FORWARDING TO ST. LOUIS.

column168: (MTPL A & B) A ROAD SWITCHER CREW SHOVED CARS FROM THE MAIN TRACK INTO A STORAGE TRACK, BUT SHOVED TOO FAR AND WENT OVER THE PROTECTIVE DERAIL ON THE OPPOSITE END OF THE STORAGE TRACK.  THE LEAD CAR IN THE SHOVING MOVE, GATX 9175, WAS LEANING AND OFF THE TRUCK CENTER PINS.  IT DID NOT, HOWEVER, FULLY OVERTURN.  THE NEXT CAR IN THE CUT WAS TILX 300910 AND IT SUSTAINED ONLY ONE DERAILED TRUCK ON THE END COUPLED TO THE GATX 9175. MONITORING OF THE CARS BY BOTH SANTA FE AND COMMUNITY RESPONDERS CONFIRMED THAT NO RELEASES OCCURRED.  ALTHOUGH THE LOCATION OF THE DERAILED CARS WAS APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET FROM THE MAIN TRACK, LOCAL FIRE OFFICIALS DID NOT PERMIT OPERATION OF ANY TRAIN TRAFFIC UNTIL THE CARS WERE UNLOADED.  THERE WAS ALSO A BRIEF CLOSURE OF SEVERAL SURFACE STREETS IN THE AREA UNTIL THE AIR MONITORING WAS COMPLETE.  BOTH CARS WERE OFF LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS FOR LOCAL DELIVERY.  TRAIN TRAFFIC RESUMED AT 0045 HOURS PT ON 11/08. FIVE TRAINS WERE DELAYED ACCOUNT THIS ACCIDENT.

THIS TANK CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHEN IT WAS BEING INSPECTED AT THE INBOUND RAIL CHECKPOINT.  IF HAD NOT ENTERED THE RAIL TRANSPORTATION PHASE.  BUT WAS RELEASED FOR RAIL TRANSPORTATION WHEN REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED.  ATSF RESPONDER FOUND AN EDUCTION TUBE TO BE MISAPPLIED AT THE TOP VALVE ARRANGEMENT AT THE REAR OF THE TANK CONTAINER.  APPARENTLY THE PIPE HAD BEEN REMOVED, BUT HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SEATED IN THE MATING/STABILIZING RECEPTACLE AT THE BOTTOM FRAME.  THIS IN TURNED CAUSED MISALIGNMENT OF THE TOP VALVE FLANGES. (THIS PIPE IS INTENDED TO BE AN OVERFLOW/SURGE PROTECTION DEVICE.)  THE UNIT WAS PERMITTED TO REMAIN ON RAILWAY PROPERTY UNTIL REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED BY THE SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR. SPILLED PRODUCT AT THE CHECKPOINT BOOTHS WAS REMOVED BY ABSORBENTS BY THE ATSF'S CONTRACTOR.

WE ARE GOING TO HOLD ONTO CONTENTS UNTIL MONDAY 11/27/95 TO ENSURE PHOTOS TAKEN BY F.A.A. ARE OK.  ON NOV. 20, 1995, THREE BOXES WERE BROUGHT TO OUR ATTENTION BY ONE OF OUR EMPLOYEES, TRACY WINTERHALDER, BECAUSE THEY APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  THOSE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED FROM THE OTHERS DURING THE REMAINDER OF THE OPERATION.  AFTER THE OPERATION I RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGES.  THE FIRST TWO THAT I RESPONDED TO WERE NORMAL SHIPMENTS OF NON-HAZARDOUS GOODS.  THE THIRD BOX I RESPONDED TO CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERAILS.  TWO WET CELL BATTERIES ONE OF WHICH WAS LEAKING.  THE PH OF THE LIQUID WAS TESTED TO CONFIRM FOR US IS TO DELIVER OR PACKAGES ON TIME.  WE TOOK THE TWO NON HAZARDOUS SHIPMENTS THAT WERE DAMAGED, PLACED THEM INTO NEW BOXES AND SENT THEM ON THEIR WAY.  SINCE THE BOX THAT CONTAINED THE BATTERIES DID ALSO CONTAIN NON HAZARDOUS GOODS, I CUT THE FLAP OF THE BOX OFF THAT CONTAINED THE SHIPPING LABEL AND ADDRESS LABEL SO IT COULD BE TAPED TO A NEW BOX. AS IT TURNED OUT WE KEPT THE CONTENTS OF BOX IN OUR FACILITY OVERNIGHT ALONG WITH THE BOX IT WAS SHIPPED IN.

VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC  LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO STABLEX CANADA, INC. LOCATED AT 760 BOUL INDUSTRIAL IN BLAINEVILLE, QUEBEC. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 10-15 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM OF 2 OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CAN TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE VAN TRAILER ONTO PAVEMENT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE.  IN ADDITION, BOTH LOCAL AND STATE AGENCIES WERE AT THE SCENE TO MONITOR THE CLEAN-UP EFFORTS AND TO PROVIDE ANY NEEDED ASSISTANCE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY, OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND CONTAINERIZED ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS FOR DISPOSAL.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, 1 X 55 GALLON DRUM OF CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS GENERATED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD.  THE ORIGINAL CONTAINERS WERE SECURED AND CONTINUED TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINER WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, CLEAN HARBORS IS CURRENTLY IMPLEMENTING A PILOT LOAD PREPARATION INSPECTION PROGRAM AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. AS WELL AS THE OTHER CLEAN HARBOR'S WATE MANIFEST FACILITIES.  THIS PROGRAM IS DESIG TO REINFORCE THE CURRENT LOAD PREPARATION ACTIVITIES AS WELL AS INCLUDED AN ACCOUNTABILITY MECHANISM FOR EACH EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE PREPARATION AND SHIPMENT OF EACH CONTAINER

ON NOVEMBER 30, 1995, AT ABOUT 3:00AM, A DRIVER OPERATING UNDER CONTRACT WITH ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC., TO DELIVER RADIOACTIVE MEDICAL PRODUCTS WAS INVOLVED IN A ONE- VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  SHE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON US 119 JUST NORTH OF LOGAN, WV, WHEN SHE CROSSED THE CENTER LINE AND NORTHBOUND LANES AND DROVE OFF THE ROAD.  THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE IN A DITCH.  ONE OF 2 PACKAGES CONTAINING RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS WAS EJECTED FROM THE TRUCK.  IT CONTAINED 4 X 200 uCi 123I DIAGNOSTIC CAPSULES PACKAGED INSIDE A FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BOX WAS FOUND INTACT IN THE SNOW ABOUT 30 FEET BEHIND THE TRUCK.  THE OTHER PACKAGES WHICH HELD 2 X 9.9 mCi 201 T1 THALLIUM CHLORIDE SOURCES WAS FOUND INTACT IN THE TRUCK.  THREE DIFFERENT FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT SINCE IT WAS UNCERTAIN IN WHICH FIRE DISTRICT THE ACCIDENT HAD OCCURRED.  THE INJURED DRIVER WAS EXTRACTED FROM THE TRUCK THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO A HOSPITAL. THE EMERGENCY SERVICES PERSONNEL MISSED THE FACT THAT THE DIAGNOSTIC CAPSULES WERE SOLID AND SUSPECTED THAT THE PACKAGE BEHIND THE TRUCK WAS LEAKING SINCE ONE SIDE OF THE BOX WAS WET FROM THE SNOW.  FOR THIS REASON, THEY CLOSED BOTH NORTHBOUND LANES FOR A SHORT TIME.  ONE NORTHBOUND LANE WAS REOPENED AT THE SUGGESTION OF THE HEALTH PHYSICIST FROM MALLINCKRODT MEDICAL WHICH WAS THE SHIPPER.  THE MALLINCKRODT HP ARRANGED FOR RADIOLOGICAL ASSISTANCE FROM THE CHARLESTON AREA MEDICAL CENTER.  THE AGENCIES OR ORGANIZATIONS CONTACTED OR INVOLVED WERE AS FOLLOWS:  LOGAN COUNTY EMERGENCY AMBULANCE SERVICE AUTHORITY, VERDUNVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, LOGAN GENERAL HOSPITAL, MALLINCKRODT MEDICAL, INC., THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, CHEMTREC, STATE RADIOLOGICAL AGENCY, STATE HEALTH DEPARTMENT, NRC REGION 11, CHARLESTON AREA MEDICAL CENTER, ASSOCIATED COURIERS, INC.  THE HEALTH PHYSICIST AND THE RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER FROM THE CHARLESTON AREA MEDICAL CENTER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND PERFORMED RADIATION LEVEL SURVEYS ON THE PACKAGES.  THEY CONCLUDED THAT THE PACKAGES HAD NOT RELEASED ANY RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS, WRAPPED THE BOXES IN PLASTIC AND PACKAGED THEM FOR TRANSPORT TO C A M C FOR DISPOSITION.  THE HP AND RSO SURVEYED THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK AND SURROUNDING AREA AND THE AREA WHERE THE 123 1 PACKAGE HAD BEEN FOUND.  ALL AREAS WERE AT BACKGROUND LEVELS.  ADDITIONALLY, SEVERAL AREAS WITHIN THE TRUCK AND THE PACKAGE SURFACES WERE WIPE TESTED FOR LOOSE CONTAMINATION.  THE WIPES WERE ANALYZED AT C A M C AND FOUND TO BE AT BACKGROUND LEVELS.  THE SCENE WAS CLEARED BY EMERGENCY SERVICES PERSONNEL AT 9:30 AM.  EMERGENCY SERVICES PERSONNEL WERE SURVEYED AT LOGAN GENERAL HOSPITAL AND WERE FOUND TO BE FREE OF RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION.  SUMMARY: A PACKAGE CONTAINING A RADIOACTIVE MEDICAL PRODUCT WAS EJECTED FROM A TRUCK WHICH WAS DRIVEN OFF A ROAD INTO A DITCH.  ANOTHER RADIOPHARMACEUTICAL PACKAGE REMAINED WITHIN THE VEHICLE.  NO RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM EITHER PACKAGE.  THE DRIVER SUSTAINED A NECK INJURY AND WAS HOSPITALIZED.

AT APPROXIMATELY  1130 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 2, A YARD CREW, WHILE SWITCHING, NOTICED PRODUCT COMING FROM TGOX 100003 IN OUR BAYONNE YARD.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT A TEAM FROM THEIR ADJACENT FACILITY. THE TEAM FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET IMPROPERLY SEATED AND REPLACED IT.

REPORT #315595 DRIVER HAD UNLOADED PARTIAL LOAD- FILLED CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK.  ATTEMPTED TO MOVE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER UNLOADING SITE, ON CUSTOMER PROPERTY.  DRIVER HAD OPENED THE DOME LID TO ESTIMATE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT REMAINING BEFORE MOVING VEHICLE.  DRIVER DID NOT SECURE DOME LID IN THE PROPER FASHION: THUS WHEN HE MOVED THE VEHICLE - SOME PRODUCT SPLASHED FROM DOME LID AREA INTO ROLLOVER PROTECTION CAGE, AND OUT THE DISCHARGE TUBE TO GROUND.  CYPRUS EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP SPILL:  JADE TRANSPORTATION WILL RETRAIN ON PROCEDURES.  PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL DRIVER ERROR.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ALKALI, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: WHEN THE SUPERVISOR WENT TO CHECK THE HAZMAT AREA HE FOUND THAT A SHIPMENT OF BATTERIES WAS LEAKING.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS.

ABF DOCKMAN JIM WILLMON HAD UNLOADED A SKID OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE AND PLACED IT ON THE DOCK IN THE HAZ MAT AREA.  WHEN HE WAS ON THE WAY BACK TO THE TRAILER TO GET ANOTHER SKID, HE NOTICED A TRAIL OF LIQUID GOING FROM THE TRAILER TO THE SKID OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE.  THE CONTAINER WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED.  THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED CHEMTREC PER OUR AGREEMENT WITH ELF ATOCHEM. ELF ATOCHEM THEN NOTIFIED THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT WITH INSTRUCTIONS ON HANDLING OF THE PRODUCT.  THE DAMAGE TO THIS FREIGHT WAS CAUSED BY ANOTHER SKID OF MATERIAL THAT WAS LOADED NEXT TO IT.  IT APPEARS THE TWO SKIDS WERE DIFFERENT HEIGHTS, AND WHILE ENROUTE TO DESTINATION, THE SKID LOADED IN FRONT OF THE ELF ATOCHEM SKID RUBBED A HOLE IN THE BOX AND THEN DAMAGED THE JUG.

WHILE UNLOADING SKID ADJACENT TO DRUM, THE DRUM WAS STRUCK BY FORK CAUSING GASH IN PLASTIC NEAR BOTTOM OF DRUM.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL AND THE SHIPPER IS GOING TO PICK UP THE DRUM WHICH WAS PLACED INTO THE HAZ MAT WAY.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN TO THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER EVAPORATED, AND THE SHIPPER IS SENDING A NEW SEAL VIA FEDEX.  ONCE THE LEAKING TOTE IS SECURED, IT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR INPECTION.

column168: UPON UNLOADING REAZ631055 ON SATURDAY NOV. 25, THE CHECKER BROUGHT IT TO MY ATTENTION THAT THE TOTE HE WAS ABOUT TO UNLOAD WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  I HAD HIM PUT THE TOTE INTO THE HAZMAT BAY AND CONTINUE TO FINISH.  I CALLED SAFETY AND REPORTED IT IMMEDIATELY.  IT SEAMS TO ME IT WAS JUST A LOOSE SEAL CAP OR A POSSIBLE DEFECTIVE SEAL.  PRODUCT DRIED ON THE OUTSIDE, THE TOTE WAS CHECKED FOR FURTHER LEAKS.  NONE WERE FOUND, SO IT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF PROBLEM.

DURING TRANSPORT FROM ONE LOCATION TO ANOTHER A DRUM OF PERC.  FELL OVER IN THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  IT WAS NOTICED AT THE NEXT STOP, WHERE THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY BEGAN RECOVERY PROCEDURES TO CLEAN UP THE RELEASE. UPON THE COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN-UP THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SAFETY-KLEEN OFFICE IN RACHO CORDOVA CA TO REPORT THE RELEASE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATLEY DRUMMED AND MANIFESTED AND LABELED.  CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A SHIFT IN DRUMS DURING TRANSPORT AND LOAD BAR DID NOT HOLD ON CONTAINER.  THIS CONTAINER TIPPED OVER AND THE LOCK RING CAME LOOSE CAUSING SPILL.
DURING UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TWO BAGS INSIDE OF SHRINK WRAP HAD SMALL RIPS.  THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED CLEAR.

WHILE THERE, ONE OF THE SCALE INSPECTORS NOTICED SOME PRODUCT IN THE SPILL DAM, AROUND THE MAN-HOLE COVER OF THE TANK. TANK WAS ISOLATED.  CYTEC INDUSTRIES WAS NOTIFIED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. RINCHEM CO., OUT OF ALBUQUERQUE, NM WAS CONTRACTED & RESPONDED TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN-UP.  THE CLEAN-UP WAS SATISFACTORY TO THE NEW MEXICO HIGHWAY PATROL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED.  THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED W/OUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: ON 11-30-95 AT 1130 HOURS I ARRIVED AT THE WORLD TRADE CENTER AT 30E. 7TH ST. ST. PAUL MINN. TO MAKE A 500 GALLON FUEL OIL DELIVERY.  THE BUILDING MAINTENANCE MAN SHOWED ME THE FILL PIPE & VENT PIPE-WE REMOVED THE FILL CAP & STARTED THE DELIVERY.  HE INFORMED ME THE TANK HAD A 1500 GALLON CAPACITY & ABOUT 750 GALLONS ON HAND.  I WATCHED & LISTENED VERY CAREFULLY, SO AS NOT TO SPILL ANY FUEL OIL AT DELIVERY SITE.  BEFORE, DURING & AFTER THE DELIVERY THE MAINTANCE MAN WAS WITH ME TO ASSURE THAT THE DELIVERY WENT WELL.  THE FILL PIPE IS AT STREET DRIVEWAY LEVEL, VENT IS ABOUT 4 FEET ABOVE & NEXT TO FILL PIPE.  TANK IS LOCATED IN A ROOM BELOW STREET LEVEL, SO DRIVER IS NOT AWARE OF ANY PROBLEM ASSOCIATED WITH THE TANK.  I FINISHED MY DELIVERY & PROCEDED TO MY NEXT DELIVERY.  I WAS TOLD LATER IN THE DAY THAT FUEL CAME OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TANK THROUGH A MAN HOLE COVER.  THIS COVER WAS HELD IN PLACE WITH SPRING LOADED BOLTS & DID NOT HAVE ANY GASKET.  WHEN THE OIL LEVEL REACHED THE TOP OF THE TANK, THE OIL WAS RELEASED AROUND COVER GASKET.  WHEN THE OIL LEVEL REACHED THE TOP OF THE TANK, THE OIL WAS RELEASED AROUND COVER INSTEAD OF COMING UP THE VENT & FILL PIPES.  THE ST. PAUL FIRE DEPT. WAS CALLED TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP.  ABOUT 40 GALLONS OF OIL WAS PUT IN A DRUM.  FLOOR DRY ABSORBANT PARTICLES WERE OUT IN ANOTHER DRUM.  ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE TO DISPOSE OF WASTE IN A PROPER MANOR.

ABF FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS MOVING THE LAST OF THREE PALLETS OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE B SOLID NOS WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF POWDER ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO RAISE THE PALLET TO INVESTIGATE A SMALL REACTION OCCURRED, CREATING A DUST CLOUD.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUT THE PALLET DOWN & BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER STRIKING THE TRAILER LOADING LIGHT.  THIS CAUSED A SPARK WHICH IGNITED THE DUST CLOUD.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED IMMEDIATELY BY THE TERMINALS SPRINKLER SYSTEM.

RECEIVED ON AACT JCK DOCK OFF MEM TRL 530065 LOADED ON TAIL END OF TRAILER.  DOCKMAN NOTED LEAKING ON BOTTOM, DOCK SUPERVISOR REMOVED TOTE TANK FROM TRAILER FOR INSPECTION.  IT FIRST APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM VALVE, LEFT ON DOCK, SAW DUST PUT AROUND TANK TO ABSORB LEAKAGE.  WHEN TANK WAS RAISED FOR INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE BOTTOM RIGHT SEAM ON FRONT OF TANK.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND CLEAN UP CREW NOTIFIED AT FERGUSON AND HARBOR.  RECOUPED AND SENT TO DESTINATION ACCEPTED BY CONSIGNEE.

column168: DRIVER WAS WEST BOUND ON I80 EAST OF WAMSUTTER, WYOMING.  THE ROAD WAS SNOWPACKED AND ICY.  ACCORDING TO THE TACH CHART, HE WAS TRAVELING CLOSE TO 60 MPH.  THE UNIT JACK-KNIFED AND SKIDDED INTO THE MEDIAN, WHERE IT ROLLED TWICE.  THE CARGO TANK RUPTURED DURING IMPACT WITH THE GROUND, SPILLING ALCOHOL ON THE GROUND.  THE SITE WHERE THE ALCOHOL WAS SPILLED WAS EXCAVATED AND NEW DIRT HAULED IN.  THE DRIVER WAS DISCHARGED FOR DRIVING TOO FAST FOR CONDITIONS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM WYNNS PRECISION INCORPORATED LOCATED AT ROUTE 42 INDUSTRIAL PARK IN LIVINGSTON, TN TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S RICHMOND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 1104 WEST ROSLYN ROAD IN COLONIAL HEIGHTS, VA.  DURING THIS STOP, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERAIL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO OVERPACK ANY CONTAINER THAT IS FOUND TO BE NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON UNDERSLIDE OF BOXLINE 3.  CONTAINER HAD A LOOSE CAP.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. SPILLED LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE.  NO PH WAS TAKEN SINCE LIQUID WAS PURPLE.  PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS WORN.  PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

OPENED FEEDER TRAILER.  FOUND PACKAGE THAT WAS WET.  REFERRED TO DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, PACKAGE DID NOT CREATE A SPILL, THE PACKAGE WAS JUST WET DUE TO A LOOSE CAP.  MOVED PACKAGE TO A SECURE AREA, HAD TEMP EMPLOYEE SEARCH FOR A NEW CARTON.  WHILE HE WAS SEARCHING, I RETURNED TO SORT AISLE.  THE TEMPORARY EMPLOYEE TOOK IT UPON HIMSELF TO REPACK THE PACKAGE AND PROCESS THROUGH THE SYSTEM FOR DELIVERY.  UPON DELIVERY DRIVER FOUND THE PACKAGE AND WAS STILL STILL LEAKING, BUT CUSTOMER WANTED PACKAGE ANYWAY.  RE-INSTRUCTED TEMPORARY EMPLOYEE ON PROPER "DMG" RESPONSE PROCEDURES.

TRAILER #515042 WAS LOADED AND MOVED INTO A STAGING AREA AWAITING DISPATCH.  AS OUR DRIVER APPROACHED THE VEHICLE, HE NOTICED THAT THE TRAILER WAS VENTING LIQUID OXYGEN AND THAT FROST WAS ON THE GROUND SURROUNDING THE REAR CABINET AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY INFORMED THE SHOP MECHANIC AND RETURNED TO THE VEHICLE WHEN HE HEARD TWO QUICK EXPLOSIONS AND SAW A FLASH OF FIRE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  BEFORE THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT COULD EXTINGUISH THE FLAMES, THE REAR PORTION OF THE TRAILER WAS SEVERELY DAMAGED.  AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE FIRE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE UNIT BEING SUBSTANTIALLY OVERFILLED.  SEVERAL FACTORS CONTRIBUTED TO THE OVERFILL.  A MALFUNCTIONING LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE PROVIDED FAULTY INFORMATION TO THE AUTOLOAD SYSTEM.  UPON OBSERVING LIQUID OXYGEN BLOWING FROM THE MAIN VENT, THE OPERATOR CEASED THE FILLING OPERATION AND OFF-LOADED PRODUCT UNTIL IT STOPPED VENTING LIQUID.  THE UNIT WAS WEIGHED, HOWEVER, THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS STILL TOO HIGH.  ONE HOUR LATER WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED, LIQUID OXYGEN WAS BLOWING OUT OF THE ROAD RELIEF VENT.  LIQUID OXYGEN AND VAPORS SATURATED THE CABINET AREA CAUSING THE TIRES TO FREEZE AND EXPLODE.  THE RESULTING SHOCK WAVES MAY HAVE IGNITED THE OXYGEN-RICH ENVIRONMENT.  TO PREVENT FUTURE OVERLOADING, SAFE LOADING WEIGHTS WILL BE ESTABLISHED FOR ALL LOX TRAILERS.  PROCEDURES WILL BE ESTABLISHED FOR PROPER HANDLING OF TRAILERS IN OVERLOADED CONDITIONS.

column168: MCCUTCHEON ENTERPRISES, INC. (MEI) WAS CONTACTED BY CLEAN HARBORS TO DELIVER A 20 CUBIC YARD ROLLOFF BOX TO YOUNG GALVANIZING.  YOUNG GALVANIZING PERSONNEL FILLED THE BOX.  WE CALLED TO PICK UP THE BOX AND, TRANSPORT TO CLEAN HARBORS DISPOSAL FACILITY IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL TO PICK UP THE BOX FOR TRANSPORTATION, THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX WERE INSPECTED FOR CONSISTENCY AND CAPACITY.  THE CAPACITY WAS APPROXIMATELY HALF FULL (10 CUBIC YARDS) AND THE CONSISTENCY APPEARED TO BE SOLID.  UPON QUESTIONING PLANT PERSONNEL AT YOUNG GALVANIZING, OUR DRIVER WAS TOLD THE WASTE IN THE BOX WAS SOLID, WHILE BEING A LITTLE DAMP. ADDITIONALLY, THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME WAS HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, AND IN SECTION J OF THE MANIFEST, THE PHYSICAL STATE IS NOTED AS BEING SOLID. THE BOX WAS ICKED UP WITHOUT INCIDENT AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY, BOTH GATES WERE CLOSED PROHIBITING ACCESS INTO THE FACILITY.  UNABLE TO SECURE PARKING ON THE STREET, THE DRIVER RESUMED DOWN THE ROAD APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE WHERE HE TURNED AROUND AND PROCEEDED BACK TO THE FACILITY.  ON A DOWNGRADE OF ROAD, A TRAFFIC LIGHT HAD TURNED RED AND UPON STOPPING, THE LOAD IN THE BOX SLID FORWARD ON THE PLASTIC BOX LINER, PUSHING LIQUIDS UP TO AND OVER THE FRONT OF THE BOX BETWEEN THE BOX AND TARP AND ONTO THE GROUND.  THROUGH TRANSPORTATION OF THIS PARTICULAR WASTE, A SEPARATION APPARENTLY HAD TAKEN PLACE WHEREBY LIQUIDS ROSE TO THE SURFACE SEPARATING FROM THE SOLIDS. THEROUGH TRANSPORTATION OF THIS PARTICULAR WASTE, A SEPARATION APPARENTLY HAD TANK PLACE WHEREBY LIQUIDS ROSE TO THE SURFACE SEPARATING FROM THE SOLIDS.  AFTER NOTICING THAT A SPILL HAD OCCURRED, THE DRIVER INFORMED CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL, WHO PHONED US IMMEDIATELY.  PERMISSION WAS GRANTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WHICH WAS COMPELTED BY CLEAN HARBORS PERSONNEL.  IN RETROSPECT, THIS WASTE MATERIAL SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN PUT IN AN OPEN TO 20 YARD ROLLOFF BOX, BUT RATHER A CLOSED TOP BOX WITH A METAL LID WHICH WOULD CONTAIN LIQUIDS, RATHER THAN A TARP.  BECAUSE WE HAD NOT TRANSPORTED THIS PARTICULAR WASTE PREVIOUS TO THIS INCIDENT, WE WERE UNAWARE THAT THIS SAPARATION WOULD OCCUR, OR THAT THERE WAS A POSSIBLITY IT MAY OCCUR.  WE WERE RELYING UPON THE EXPERTISE OF OUR CLIENT.  CLEAN HARBORS, WHO HAD INFORMATION ON THE WASTE (IE, SAMPLES, ANALYSIS) TO DETERMINE THE PROPER SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THESE CLOSED TOP BOXES ARE A PART OF OUR FLEET AND COULD HAVE BEEN UTILIZED IF REQUESTED.  IN THE FUTURE, DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO EXAMINE THE CONTENTS OF THE BOXES FOR WETNESS BEFORE THEY PICK UP FOR TRANSPORTATION, AND ALSO TO INCLUDE AS PART OF THEIR SAFETY CHECK, AN INSPECTION OF THE CARGO TO DETERMINE IF SEPARATION OF LIQUIDS HAVE OCCURRED DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER OUT OF CHICAGO.  UPON OPENING TRAILER, NOTICED LIQUID ON FLOOR FROM A PUNCTURED DRUM. THE DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED BY A TOWMOTOR BLADE WHEN A SKID WAS LOADED ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  NO DUNNAGE OR EMPTY PALLETS WERE USED TO BLOCK IN THE LOAD.  IF THIS WOULD HAVE BEEN USED, IT WOULD HAVE PROBABLY PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT FROM OCCURRING.

column168: HOLE IN BOTTOM OF EACH DRUM WAS CAUSED BY NAILS STICKING OUT OF SKID USED AND WORE HOLES IN BOTTOM OF EACH OF THE DRUMS.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, PROPER DONNAGE NEEDS TO BE USED WHEN HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FOR INSTANCE, CARDBOARD NEEDS TO BE PLACED ON A NAIL-FREE SKID TO PREVENT FUTURE INSTANCES.

A SUPERVISOR DISCOVERED A LEAKING DRUM AND REPORTED IT TO THE OPERATIONS MANAGER. UPON INSPECTION, THE MANAGER AND SUPERVISOR DECIDED TO RECOUP THE DRUM INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK. THEY PLACED THE DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT AND ALSO PLACED IT INTO AN OVERPACK. CHEMTRAC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER. MR. JERRITT FROM RHONE POULENC CONTACTED THE TERMINAL AND OFFERED ASSISTANCE. THE ABF SAFETY AND SECURITY DEPARTMENT ADVISED TO VENTILATE THAT END OF THE DOCK FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES JUST TO AVOID ANY FUMES. THERE WAS STILL A STRONG SMELL EVEN THOUGH ONLY APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP HAD LEAKED. SOMEONE ANONYMOUSLY CONTACTED TGE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO RESPONDED. THE FIRE DEPT. HAD THE MEN LEAVE THE DOCK AREA AND REMAIN IN THE YARD. THEY THEN ENCOURAGED THEM TO SEEK ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION THEY THOUGHT THEY NEEDED. WE HAD FOUR MEN GO TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION BUT ALL WERE RELEASED IN GOOD HEALTH. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN CONTACTED THE DEP SO THEY COULD COME OUT AND DO AN AIR SAMPLE. THEIR FINDINGS WERE NEGATIVE. EVERYONE RESUMED WORK WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENCE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2330 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 28, CONRAIL TRAIN WAMA21 DERAILED WHEN A 100# ARA RAIL BROKE UNDER MOVEMENT AT MILE POST 175.5 ON THE MONTREAL SECONDARY IN BOMBAY, NY.  TANK CAR UTLX 66490 CAME TO REST 120 DEGREES FROM VERTICAL.  AS A RESULT THE VACCUUM RELIEF VALVE BEGAN TO DRIP PRODUCT AT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON AN HOUR.  ALL MATERIAL WAS CAUGHT AND PLACED IN A SPILL BARREL.  THE NEW YORK DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL WAS ON HAND MONITORING THE PROGRESS.  THE CAR WAS RIGHTED AT 1420 HOURS ON THE 29TH AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS PLACED ON WHEEL SETS AND MOVED, UNDER SPECIAL HANDLING, TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE EMPLOYEE WAS OFF LOADING A DRUM AS PUNCTURED WITH THE FORKLIFT CREATING A HOLE AND THE LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER AND LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER TO THE FLOOR IN FRONT OF THE DOCK DOOR.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO CONTAIN THE LEAK WITH A SPILL KIT, BUT WERE NOT SUCCESSFUL.  WE PROCEEDED TO CALL THE SHIPPER IN ORDER TO OBTAIN DATA SHEET AND MORE INFORMATION BUT THIS TOOK SOME TIME.  AT THAT POINT IT WAS DECIDED THAT WE WERE TO CALL THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  THE REMAINING PORTION OF THE MATERIAL THAT WAS IN THE DRUM WAS DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENT CO.

OF ENVIRONMENTAL, HEALTH, AND NATURAL RESOURCES.  THE SPILL HAPPENED BECAUSE THE CUSTOMER USED THE WRONG HOSE (VAPOR HOSE) TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT.  THIS HOSE IS NOT DESIGNATED FOR THIS USE. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AS OUR DRIVER ENTERED THE LEFT HAND CURVE (WHERE HE ROLLED THE TRUCK), HE KNEW THE FRESH PAVEMENT WAS WET.  HALF WAY THROUGH THE CURVE HE NOTICED A LARGE ONCOMING TRUCK SO HE MOVED HIS RIG TO THE OUTSIDE OF HIS LANE TO GIVE THE ONCOMING TRUCK EXTRA CLEARANCE.  IT WAS AT THIS POINT WHERE HE TOOK HIS FOOT OFF THE FUEL PEDAL AND THE JAKE BRAKE ENGAGED CAUSING IMMEDIATE LOSS OF TRACTION OF ALL DRIVE TIRES.  ALTHOUGH THE DRIVER APPLIED FUEL AND TURNED THE TRUCKS STEERING WHEELS TO THE RIGHT, HE NEVER REGAINED TRACTION AND THE LOADED TRAILER PUSHED THE AFT END OF THIS TRUCK FORWARD WHILE THE CAB CONTINUED TO VEER TO THE LEFT TOWARD THE EMBANKMENT. AT THIS POINT THE TRUCK AND TRAILER HAD ASSUMED AN L" CONFIGUATION AS IT SLID ONTO THE GUARDRAIL FINALLY COMING TO REST WITH THE TRUCK ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE ON TOP OF THE GUARD RAIL AND THE TRAILER UPRIGHT. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH FRESH SOIL.  THE GUARD RAIL WAS REPLACED TO CAL-TRANS SATISFACTION.  AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT, THE DRIVER WAS DISCIPLINED AND JAKE BRAKE USE WAS RESTRICTED TO DRY DOWNHILL CONDITIONS.

column168: ON 110295 AT APPROXIMATELY 9PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, CARL BROUGHTON THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED. REEDER ATTEMPTED TO INSTALL THE BOLTS. ONE BOLT TIGHTENED PROPERLY, THE OTHERS WOULD NOT TIGHTEN BECAUSE THE HOLES WERE STRIPPED. REEDER NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER HIRED RESCAR TANK CAR REPAIR COMPANY TO MAKE TEMPORARY REPAIRS TO GET THE CAR TO DESTINATION.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ELKO NV. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR UP 70197 AND NOTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING, WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED 8 OF 8 SWING BOLTS LOOSE ON THE MANWAY COVER. MGR. RODABOUGH REPAIRED THE CAR BY TIGHTENING THE BOLTS. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, MR. JEFF BOTWENIC ASSIGNED CASE #40031. THE SHIPPER AMOCO OIL WAS ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND STATED THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ELKO NV. MGR. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR GAPX 9076 AND NOTED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED. MGR. RODABOUGH INSTALLED A NEW BS & B 100# DISC IN SAFETY VENT MOUNTED ON MANWAY COVER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. MR. JEFF BOTWENIC ASSIGNED CASE #40032. THE SHIPPER GEORGIA GULF WAS NOTIFIED, SPEAKING WITH MR. THURMAN BELL, THE SHIPPER SUPERVISOR. HE ADVISED HE WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

SAHM BALLANCE WAS ADVISED BY GARY NOLAN THE STOCKTON TOWER OPERATOR THAT TANKCAR UTLX-11011 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. SAHM BALLANCE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND FOUND THE RUPTURE DISC WAS BLOWN. THE RUPTURE DISC REMOVED WAS AN OSECO RC-100. SAHM BALLANCE DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT DISC AT THE TIME. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND PROVIDED A CONTACT AT JONES HAMILTON CO. WHO ADVISED HE WOULD BRING AN OSECO RE-100 DISC TO THE YARD. THE CAR WAS PLACED IN BAD ORDER STATUS. THE FOLLOWING MORNING THE DISC WAS RECEIVED AND REPLACED. THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ADVISED BY SUPV. YARD OPERATIONS AT SEATTLE THAT A TRAIN CREW HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR. THE CREW ISOLATED THE TANK CAR AND LEFT THE AREA. WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

UPRR BOWL CAR FOREMAN K.D. WALLACE REPORTED THAT A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA WAS COMING FROM ACFX 18642 IN TRACK 107. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET REPSPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE PACKING GLAND RETAINER ASSEMBLY, WHICH IS SECURED BY MEANS OF 2 NUTS, WAS LOOSE. PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 70 PSI. THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. CHEMTREC CHRIS YOUNG WAS ADVISED AT 0145 HRS. REPORT #40008.

REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY STEVE TROUTMAN MYO NEFF YARD ADVISING CREWS REPORTED STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CARS IN TRACK 303, NEFF YARD. INSPECTION BY MR. STINE AND MR. TROUTMAN DEVELOPED CAR GATX 92238 WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE "REGO" SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. PRESSURE ON CAR WAS 30 PSI. MR. STINE NOTED AN "O" RING LAYING ON THE PRESSURE PLATE ALSO A METAL TAG FROM THE SAFETY VALVE WHICH SHOWED THE FOLLOWING; "GLENCO VALVE SERVICE, (DATE) 3-6-90, (TAG) 255-234, (SET TEST) 280.5, (CUST) GATX 67, (ID#) 003A031, (SERIAL) BTM 063, (O RING) BUNNA". DISMANTLED THE SAFETY VALVE TO "O" RING RETAINER THEN REMOVED THE RETAINER AND REPLACED THE "O" RING. AFTER SECUREMENT THE CARE WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TANSPORTATION. IN CHECKING THE "O" RING THAT WAS REMOVED IT APPEARED IN NEW CONDITION AND HAD RECENTLY BEEN INSTALED. THIS INFORMATION FURNISHED TO MR. JACK CURRY AT FARMLAND INDUSTRIES.

column168: ON 11/02/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 03:05 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ILN WILMINGTON, OH IN OUR SORT FACILITY.  RESPONDING TO THE SPILL WAS HAZARDOUS MATERAIL SPILL TECHNICIAN RANDY WILIAMS UPON HIS INSPECTION OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DAMP.  FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY 18 RECEPTACLES OF HAIR SPRAY AND OTHER MISC. HAIR CARE PRODUCTS.  THE HAIR SPRAY IS REGULATED BY AIR.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE BOX THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERAIL AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT ALSO CONTAINED NO MARKINGS OR LABELS EXCEPT AN AIRWAYBILL LABEL.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE FRICTION AND RUBBING OF THE INNER CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE 03:47.

ON 11/12/95 SORT SUPERVISOR, GARY LEE REPORTED A SPILL.  HAZARDOUS MATERAIL COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A WET FIBREBOARD BOX.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE INNER CONTENTS TO CONTAIN 4 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES CONTAINING TIRE CLEANING PRODUCTS.  THERE WAS ONE RECEPTACLE THAT LEAKED ALL OF ITS CONTENTS.  THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED WAS FLAMMABLE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE A REGULATED MATERIAL WHEN SHIPPED BY AIR. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABLES TO INDICATE THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERAIL AND THE PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS POSSIBLE RUBBING AND ABRADING OF THE INNER CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE 01:28.

UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A LIQUID EMITTING AN ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX THEY FOUND IT TO CONTAIN A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROX 1/2 OZ OF LIQUID WAS LOST.  THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLE WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WHICH WAS LOOSE. column168: ON 11/07/95 HAZMAT SORT LEAD, RHONDA CLONCH REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THERE WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS ISOLATED.  TECHNICIAN MCLAUGHLIN DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE HE FOUND FOUR METAL RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

TECHNICIAN ADKINS USED SOME LITMUS PAPER TO SEE IF THE LIQUID WAS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  THE PAPER SHOWED THIS WAS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL. THE CAUSE FOR THE LEAK IS UNKNOWN.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: FOUND LEAKING PACKAGES ON BELT, CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.  REMOVED PACKAGE AND SECURED AREA.  SOILED BOX WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH SOLUSORB AND PROCESSED THROUGH D.M.P.

PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM A CONTAINER.  IT WAS PLACED ON A BELTLOADER TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO THE BELLY OF AN AIRCRAFT.  DUE TO THE SLOPE OF THE BELTLOADER AND THE TYPE OF CONTAINER, THE CONTAINER FELL OVER.  THIS CAUSED THE LIQUID NITROGEN TO LEAK OUT.  AT THAT TIME, THE BELTLOADER WAS STOPPED, THE TWO EMPLOYEES IN THE CONTAINER LEFT THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY.  KEVIN O'NEAL SUPERVISOR ALSO WAS PRESENT.  HE CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDERS GEORGE LAWRENCE & ROB HINDS.  KEVIN HAD THE UPS SHIPPING PAPER IN HAND FOR THE SUBSTANCE AND GAVE IT TO GEORGE & ROB WHEN THE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  GEORGE & ROB FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE & THE PROPER UPS RESPONSE SHEET SINCE THEY HAD THE SHIPPING PAPER.  AFTER PUTTING ON THE PROPER P.P.E. INCLUDING SCBA THEY RESPONDED TO THE CONTAINER.  BY  LOWERING THE BELT OF THE BELTLOADER AND STANDING THE CONTAINER UPRIGHT, THE SPILLAGE WAS HALTED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL DISPERSED INTO THE AIR LEAVING NO RESIDUE.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA & LOCAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  ADDITIONAL PACKAGING AT THE BASE TO PREVENT TIPPING MAY HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 22, 1995, AT APPROX. 1700 HOURS, UTLX 86959, LOAD, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE DOME AREA OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' BEAUMONT, TEXAS YARD. NO PRODUCT MADE CONTACT WITH ANY PERSON, NOR DID THE PRODUCT REACH THE GROUND. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE HOUSE TRACK FOR REPAIRS. THE SHIPPER (HUNTSMAN CORPORATION) DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE SITE, ARRIVING AT 1930 HOURS, TO REPAIR THE LEAK. AFTER EXAMINING THE TANK CAR, THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE (JIM GILLESPIE) REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER WAS MIS-ALIGNED. THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE REPOSITIONED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER ALLOWING THE TANK CAR TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

AT 2005 ON SUNDAY, NOV. 19, 1995, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM OUR MAIN OPERATIONS CONTROL CENTER REGARDING FLIGHT 89 ENROUTE TO LOS ANGELES FROM NEWARK, NEW JERSEY. A FLIGHT ATTENDANT OVERHEARD A PASSENGER TALKING ABOUT HAVING FIREWORKS IN HER CHECKED BAG. THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT TOLD THE CAPTAIN AND HE ELECTED TO LAND AT THE CLOSET UNITED AIRLINES FACILITY. HE CALLED THE CLEVELAND CONTROL TOWER FOR LANDING INFO AND THEY PUT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ON A LEVEL ONE ALERT WHICH HAS THE TRUCKS STANDBY IN QUARTERS. WHEN THE FLIGHT ARRIVED THE CLEVELAND POLICE, OUR PASSENGER AGENT AND I ASKED THE PASSENGER, CLAUDIA LEWIS, TO COME OUT ONTO THE JETWAY. WE GOT HER CLAIM CHECK AND BROUGHT HER BAG UP FROM THE CARGO DEPARTMENT. THE POLICE AND MS. LEWIS WENT THROUGH IT AND REMOVED A CARDBOARD TUBE THREE INCHES LONG BY ONE INCH IN DIAMETER. IT HAD A FUSE IN ONE END. WE TOLD THE CAPTAIN OF OUR ACTION, ALLOWED MS. LEWIS AND HER BAG BACK ON BOARD, TOPPED OFF THE FUEL AND DISPATCHED THE TRIP. UNITED IS FILING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL AVIATION REGULATIONS PART 175.45. UNITED MAKES NO DETERMINATION OR ADMISSION BY VIRTURE OF THIS FILING AS TO THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.

AT 0830 HRS. ON FRIDAY THE 11TH DAY OF NOVEMBER 1995 MGR. C.T.S. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. RICK SORRELL, MGR. MECH MTCE POCATELLO, THAT TANKCAR CGTX26189 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  HE ALSO ADVISED THAT IT HAD BEEN SET OUT ON THE HEATING PLANT SPUR, FOR REPAIR.  INSPECTION REVEALED A LOOSE CONNECTION WHERE THE 3" BALL VALVE CONNECTS TO THE DISCHARGE PIPE.  THE TANK HAD SOME PRESSURE WHICH FORCED THE PRODUCT UP THE PIPE AND IT LEAKED AT THE THREADS AND RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  MGR. RODABOUGH RELEASED THE PRESSURE, THROUGH THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND REMOVED THE BALL VALVE, RE-TAPED THE THREADS AND REAPPLIED THE VALVE, USING A 36" PIPE WRENCH.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  MR. JEFF BOTWENIC ASSIGNED CASE #40182.  MR. DENNIS BENASSI OF SHELL OIL CANADA WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  HE STATED THAT THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

ON FRIDAY, 11/10/95 YARD PERSONNEL AT UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD ABOVE TANK CAR GATX 49106.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITH OUT INCIDENT.  UPRR SUPERVISOR OF YARD OPERATIONS, ERROLL TROXCLAIR NOTIFIED UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON.  ROBINSON RESPONDED AND FOUND THE LEAKAGE TO BE THE RESULT OF A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY IS A MIDLAND AIR CONNECTION BAFFLE TYPE LOCATION ON THE MANWAY COVER AT THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  THE FAILED DISC WAS A BS&B MODEL TC, 100#.  ROBINSON INSTALLED A NEW DISC OF THE SAME KIND.  THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR. CHRIS YOUNG OF CHEMTREC AND MR. DAN CROCKER, ACID PLANT OPERATOR AT DOE RUN, HERCULANEUM, MISSOURI.  CROCKER AND YOUNG WERE ADVISED OF THE FAILED DISC AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN BY ROBINSON.

ON 11/23/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 0323 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN THE SECONDARY 3 AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  INSIDE THIS FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND 2  X 8 FL OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES OF JEAN NATE' PERFUME.  1 OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE SCREW-TYPE PUMP SPRAY CLOSURE, WHICH CAUSED ALL OF THE PRODUCT TO SPILL.  ALSO IN THIS FIBREBOARD BOX WERE 10 X 1 FL OZ GLASS BOTTLES WITH ATOMIZERS OF UNFORGETABLE PERFUME.  NONE OF THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE LEAKING.  THERE WERE OTHER MISCELLANEOUS, NON-HAZARDOUS COSMETICS INSIDE THIS FIBREBOARD BOX, BUT NO ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED. THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column168: ON 11-10-95 SPILL TECHNICIAN ALAN HENDERSON FOUND A LEAKING SHIPMENT DURING THE SORT OPERATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PACKED IN A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS. THE LEAKING LIQUID WAS PH'D, PH WAS NEUTRAL. ALAN OPENED THE BOX, INSIDE HE FOUND 3 METAL AEROSOL CANS 170ML EACH OF PANA SPRAY. EACH CAN INDICATED FLAMMABLE PLG GAS. THESE AEROSOLS DID NOT LEAK. ALSO PACKAGED INSIDE THIS SHIPMENT ARE 4 -1 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF PODO LIQUID. EACH PLASTIC CONTAINER HAD A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH PACKAGING TAPE AROUND EACH CLOSURE. ONE OF 4 CONTAINERS LEAKAD APPROXIMATELY 3 QUARTS. ON THE OUTSIDE OF EACH CONTAINER IS A PRODUCT LABEL WITH THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: RED FLAMMABLE SYMBOL. CONTENTS; PODO LIQUID, 45.5% ETHANOL, 1.5% ETHER, LEMONGRASS, H20. THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL USED IN THIS SHIPMENT. ON ONE END OF THE OUTER BOX, AN ORIENTATION ARROW HAS BEEN MARKED ON THE BOX IN BLACK INK. THIS ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE 2 NEW PLASTIC BAGS, TAGGED TO BE HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION IS COMPLETE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, CERTIFICATIONS OR OTHER ATTACHMENTS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATED THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

column168: 00:50 - 11-14-95 SORT SUPERVISOR BETTY COCHRAN REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT TO HAZ MAT DISPATCH. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AS A BLACK LIQUID, STRONG ODOR, 2 EMPLOYEE'S IN CONTACT. SPILL WAS LOCATED IN B BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. HAZ MAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICAN RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL WE DONNED AIR PURIFING RESPIRATORS AND APPROACHED THE SPILL. WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX SITTING ON THE FLOOR LEAKING BLACK LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. WE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND A ONE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE. THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS AND WAS UNSECURE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE. THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL INSIDE THE BOX. WE RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS TAGGED IT TO BE HELD FOR CONFIRMATION OF CONTENTS DUE TO EMPLOYEE INVOLVMENT. THERE WAS UNIDENTIFIED PAPWERWORK INSIDE THE BOX. IT HAD BEEN LEAKED UPON BY THE BLACK LIQUID AND WAS ILLEGIBLE. THE SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT AND PLACED IN THE SECURITY CAGE. MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET REQUESTED AND RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER. MSDS INDICATED FLASHPOINT IS 120 DEGREES F., AND PRODUCT NAME IS "PETROLEUM ASPHALTEMULSION". THERE WERE NO LABELS, MARKINGS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS OF THIS SHIPMENT IS A REGULATED MATERIAL. SHIPMENT REMAINS UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A BOX EMITTING AN ODOR AND LEAKING.  WHILE INSPECTING THIS SHIPMENT THEY DISCOVERED A FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINING SEVERAL PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THE REGULATED MATERIAL THAT LEAKED WAS WOODPAL WOODSTRIPPER.  WE CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURE AND FOUND THAT THE ITEMS ALSO LABELED WRONG. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING POSSIBLE RUBBING AND ABRADING OF THE INNER CONTENTS AND NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE INNER CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATING BY THE FAA.  THEY WERE CLEAR OF SCENE AT 04:31.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: UNIT 1 PULLED UP TO THE STOP SIGN AT THE JUNCTION OF KY 160 & KY 80.  UNIT 2 WAS TRAVELING EAST ON KY 80.  UNIT 1 PULLED ONTO KY 80 IN THE PATH OF UNIT 2.  UNIT 2 STRUCK UNIT 1.  UNIT 2 THEN LOST CONTROL, SLID SIDEWAYS AND OVERTURNED.  UNIT 2, LOADED WITH DIESEL FUEL, SKIDDED 250' ON ITS SIDE.  A SMALL CRACK OCCURRED IN THE TANK ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO LEAK OUT OF TANKER.  LEWIS TRANSPORT WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTION WAS TAKEN.  THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED:  EPA, NRC, STATE FIRE MARSHAL, INSURANCE, FIRE DEPARTMENT, LEWIS TERMINAL MANAGER, MIKE MCCURRY - LEWIS EMERGENCY SPILL TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL THE EPA AND FIRE DEPARTMENT CONSTRUCTED DIKES TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND CONTAIN THE SPILL.  MIKE MCCURRY ARRIVED WITH THE SPILL TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE TANK FROM THE SIDE AND PUMP THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE OVERTURNED UNIT ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  WHEN COMPLETED, THE TANKER WAS UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  ENVIRO-PRO, AN OUTFIT OUT OF PIKEVILLE, KY, CAME IN AND DID THE CLEAN-UP.  PHOTOGRAPHS WERE TAKEN OF THE SCENE AND AREA BEING USED IN THE COMPANY SAFETY MEETING TO DISCUSS SAFETY RULES SUCH AS SEAT BELT USE AND SPEED MANAGEMENT.

INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ROD WAS BROKEN.  STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND WAS WEDGED AROUND VALVE ROD AND TWO NEW BOLTS AND NUTS HAD BEEN APPLIED TO GLAND.  WEDGED TEFLON PACKING BETWEEN VALVE ROD AND STUFFING BOX APPLYING TEFLON GLUE-GEL AROUND AND OVER VALVE ROD AND RESECURED PACKING GLAND, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  TOM ROGGERS, WICKLAND OIL TERMINALS, ALICE MARTIN, COASTAL CHEM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1215 HRS. ON 11/29/95 TANK CAR DOWX 5985 WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT IN THE LIVONIA, LA. YARD.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1330 HRS. ON 11/29/95, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAUX WAS NOTIFIED BY REGIONAL DIRECTOR G.J. GRANNAN OF THE DERAILMENT.  AT 1615 HRS. ON 11/29/95, AGENT BOUDREAUX ARRIVED AT THE DERAILMENT SITE AND MET WITH SUPERINTENDENT JEFF CRANDELL, MTO WAYNE WOODALL, MCM DAVE MEYERS, DOW CHEMICAL REP. DEAN SMITH, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE TROOPER COWART AND LA.  DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAYNE MEYERS.  TANK CAR DOWX 5985 WAS LAYING ON ITS LEFT SIDE WITH EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE JACKET.  AGENT BOUDREAUX & DEAN SMITH WERE UNABLE TO TELL WHAT IF ANY DAMAGE HAD BEEN CAUSED TO THE MAIN TANK.  THERE WAS A SLIGHT LEAK DRIPPING FROM THE VACUME RELIEF VALVE.  A PLASTIC BUCKET WAS PLACED IN A POSITION TO CATCH ANY PRODUCT THAT DRIPPED. ABOUT 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM THE VALVE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ADAPTER AND AUXILIARY VALVE HAD BEEN SHEARED AWAY EXPOSING THE INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH WAS NOT LEAKING.  AGENT BOUDREAUX & SMITH'S CREW INSTALLED A 1/4 INCH METAL PLATE WITH RUBBER GASKET MATERIAL OVER THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPENING TO PROTECT AGAINST ANY POSSIBLE LEAKAGE WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS UPRIGHTED.  AT 2140 HRS. ON 11/29/95, TANK CAR DOWX 5985 WAS UPRIGHTED WITHOUT ANY  FURTHER INCIDENT.  ALL RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF BY DEAN SMITH OF DOW CHEMICAL CO.  THIS TANK CAR WAS SPOTTED ON THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRACK FOR POSSIBLE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TANK CAR. REMARKS ARE THE SAME AS 95121024A.

UPRR MTO BOB TIPPIT REPORTED THAT TANK CAR ASTX 5055 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  HE HAD ISOLATED THE CAR PENDING REPAIRS.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE AT THE CAP.  THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED VIA THE AIR INLET VALVE AND THE LEAKAGE STOPPED.  THE LIQUID LINE CAP WAS REMOVED, THE THREADS TAPED, AND THE CAP REPLACED.  THE LIQUID LINE FLANGES AND GASKET APPEARED WORN, BUT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED IF THEY ALSO LEAKED BECAUSE OF THE PRODUCT FLOW FROM THE CAP.  AG LIME AND SODIUM BICARBONATE WERE USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE CAR AND GROUND.  THE CAR AND GROUND WAS SPRAYED DOWN WITH WATER.  TRACY JACKSON, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AT 1325 HRS., RPT 40490. FRED SCOTT, ASARCO, CALLED BACK AND WAS ADVISED OF THE ACTIONS TAKEN.  HE WAS TOLD THAT THE CAR WAS ADVISED OF THE ACTIONS TAKEN.  HE WAS TOLD THAT THE CAR WOULD BE SPOTTED TO THE CONSIGNEE ON WEDNESDAY, 11-29-95.  MR. SCOTT STATED THAT THERE SHOULD NOT BE A PROBLEM WITH PRESSURE BUILD-UP SINCE ALL THE PRESSURE WAS RELEASED, THE WEATHER WAS COLD, AND THE CAR WAS WHITE.   ROBERT NIPPER, DELTA DISTRIBUTORS 903-759-7151, WAS ADVISED OF THE CAR STATUS AND CONDITION.  HE SAID THEY WOULD CHECK AND POSSIBLY CHANGE OUT THE FLANGE GASKET PRIOR TO OFF-LOADING AND WOULD TAG THE LIQUID LINE CAP TO BE CHECKED AND REPAIRED.

column168: AT 2030 HRS ON 11-24-95, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS DAVE MARTINEZ REPORTED TANK TILX 300489, CONTAINING RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, LOCATED ON EAST RECEIVING TRACK 4 TO BE LEAKING.  INSPECTION OF CAR BY MGR LERCH SOURCE OF RELEASE DUE TO A FAILED THEROMETER WELL WITHING THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR. RESIDUE VAPOR WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TAIL HOLES ON THE CAP, ALSO NOTED TO BE MISSING WAS THE O-RING LOCATED AT THE BASE OF THE CAP THREADS OF THE THEROMETER WELL.  AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF LEAK, MGR LERCH CHECKED PRESSURE OF CAR WHICH GAUGED AT 64 P.S.I.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED BY CLAMPING A RUBBER SLEEVE AT THE BASE OF THE THEROMETER WELL AND BY PLUGGLING THE OPPOSITE END OF THE SLEEVE WITH A STEE PLUG AND CLAMP.  A 2 1/2 INCH PIECE OF P.V.C. PIPE WAS THEN SLIPPED OVER THE RUBBER SLEEVE TO KEEP IF FROM EXPANDING.  UPON CONTAINMENT OF THE RELEASE, THE CAR WAS STENCILED ON LEFT AND RIGHT SIDES BY THE REPORTING MARKS, "LEAKY TANK, DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED".  AN "X" WAS PAINTED ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER AND THE THEROMETER WELL WAS RED TAGGED "LEAKS", ON 11-30-95, AN EXEMPTION WAS GRANTED TO SHIP THE CAR IN ITS CURRENT CONDITION TO BERWIND RAILWAY SERVICE; NEODESHA, KS.  FOR REPAIR; EXEMPTION #DOT-E11603. column168: PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AT UNLOAD. EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD A RUPTURED CAP WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. THE CAP WERE SECURED. CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED. PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

WHILE STRIPPING THE TRAILER, THE DOCKMAN FOUND THE DRUM WITH A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE SIDE.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON ITS SIDE AND ISOLATED IN THE TRAILER.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTIONS RECEIVED ON RECOUPING THE DRUM.  IT WAS PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK, MARKED AND LABELED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR AUTHORITY.  AN IMPROPER LOAD REPORT WILL BE COMPLETED IN ORDER TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: DURING SORT OPERATIONS, PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED DUE TO LEAKAGE.  THE INNER CONTAINER APPARENTLY RUPTURED.  IT IS NOT KNOWN WHETHER THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT OR DAMAGED IN HANDLING.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO REQUESTED THE CONTAINER BE RETURNED TO THEM IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR FURTHER REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATIONS AFTER INADVERTENTLY FALLING OVER ON ITS SIDE ON THE BELT.  FREE FLOWING LIQUID NITROGEN WAS NOTICED ALONG WITH THE VAPOR COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELLING ON THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE TO INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS CONTAINED A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED WHERE SPECIAL AGENT LUKE SHELTON WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

PERSONNEL WERE CLEARED FROM AREA, PUT ON PPD, REMOVED DAMAGED MATERIAL TO PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER.  PROCESSED PACKAGE USING THE DECISION TREE, THE FLAMMABLE RESPONSE SHEET AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PROCEURES. DISPOSED OF WASTE THROUGHT DMP PROGRAM & STORED EQUIPMENT.  INTIALLY PH'D A 4 USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE TO A 7 BEFORE USING CLAY ABSORBANT.

PRODUCT BEGAN LEAKING FROM ONE COMPARTMENT DOME LID.  THE FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE CALLED. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE WAS TO DO CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.  ALL CITY, STATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.
